      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "DOMAIN",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "The helix-turn-helix (HTH) motif in the cytoplasmic domain of the N-terminus is involved in the formation of spirals to maintain the rigid rod shape. As this protein is anchored in the cytoplasmic membrane, the HTH motif may contribute to protein-protein interactions to form the RodZ helix, which is localized beneath the cytoplasmic membrane. The C-terminal domain may be critical for determination of the rod shape by probably interacting with enzymes required for synthesis of the peptidoglycan layer, including PBPs in the periplasm"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "annotationType": "ANNOTATION",
        "comment": {
          "commentType": "FUNCTION",
          "texts": [
            {
              "value": "Cytoskeletal protein that is involved in cell-shape control through regulation of the length of the long axis"
            }
          ]
        }
